                            <comment id="12883730" author="mikem" created="Tue, 29 Jun 2010 23:22:45 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;while &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DERBY-700&quot; title=&quot;Derby does not prevent dual boot of database from different classloaders on Linux and Mac OS X&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;DERBY-700&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;DERBY-700&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; is about dual boot and class loaders, a lot of the discussion applies.  The issue was how to prevent dual booting when no java locking mechanism worked.  This issue seems similar to the state on the CDC platform.  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On windows platforms (so far) the underlying system implementation of the jvm has provided a file locking mechanism such that one can not delete a file that another jvm has open.  Derby uses this as its first step&lt;br/&gt;
in preventing dual boot (originally this was the only method when the original product existed before jdk 1.4).  Even with the use of new locking protocols, this mechanism is the first step and then other routines are used&lt;br/&gt;
if it is not available.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13672057" author="knutanders" created="Sat, 1 Jun 2013 12:28:27 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Now that CDC support has been removed from trunk, it&apos;s unlikely that this feature will be implemented. Dag, are you OK with closing the issue as Won&apos;t Fix?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13674288" author="dagw" created="Tue, 4 Jun 2013 12:17:52 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Yup, fine with me. Go ahead.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
